<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Buildings: Advanced Techniques
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Bulk editing polygons, filtering facets, transferring, cloning, moving, and deleting.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Polygons and Bulk Editing
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Facets that form a <Bold>closed polygon</Bold> (a connected loop of walls/doors with
        no gaps) are automatically grouped in the <Bold>Polygons</Bold> column on the right
        side of the Buildings tab.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Polygon groups allow you to edit all facets in a closed structure simultaneously, which
        is much faster than editing each facet individually. This is especially useful when you
        need to change the height, style, or other properties of an entire building layer at once.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Opening the Bulk Facet Edit Dialog
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select a building from the Buildings list.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                In the <Bold>Polygons</Bold> column, <Bold>double-click</Bold> a polygon group.
                The <Bold>Bulk Facet Edit</Bold> window appears.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Understanding the Bulk Edit Interface
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Bulk Facet Edit window shows all property values for the facets in the selected
        polygon. Each property has a color-coded indicator:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold Foreground="#90EE90">Green (=)</Bold> — All facets in the polygon have the
                <Bold>same value</Bold> for this property. The shared value is displayed.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold Foreground="#FFD700">Yellow (≠)</Bold> — Facets have <Bold>different values</Bold>
                for this property. The field shows a mixed/empty state.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Making Changes
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Modify any values you want to update. For example, change <Bold>Height</Bold> from
                4 to 8 to make all walls in the polygon 2 storeys tall.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Untick the checkbox</Bold> next to a property if you do not want to update
                it. Only properties with checked boxes will be applied to the facets.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                You can also change the <Bold>base style</Bold> by selecting a new style from the
                style picker. This replaces the Style Index for all facets in the polygon.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click <Bold>Apply to All</Bold> to commit the changes. All facets in the polygon
                are updated with the new values.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_bulk_edit.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Bulk Facet Edit dialog showing property values with green (=) and yellow (≠) indicators, checkboxes, and Apply to All button
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A2A3A" BorderBrush="#4A4A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#B0B0E0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>Use bulk editing when you need to increase building height uniformly, change all walls to a different style, or adjust Y offsets for an entire layer. It's much faster than selecting and editing each facet individually.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- FILTERING -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Filtering Facets by Type
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Complex buildings can contain dozens or hundreds of facets — walls, doors, ladders,
        fences, cables, and gates all mixed together. The <Bold>color pill</Bold> filtering
        system lets you quickly show only one facet type at a time.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        How to Filter
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select a building from the Buildings list.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                At the top of the <Bold>Facets</Bold> panel, you'll see a row of colored pills
                corresponding to each facet type (green for walls, orange for ladders, etc.).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Click a color pill</Bold> to filter the Facets list to show only that type.
                For example, click the <Bold>orange pill</Bold> to see only ladders.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click the pill again (or click <Bold>All</Bold>) to clear the filter and show
                all facets.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_color_filter.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Facets panel with color pill filter buttons active, showing filtered list of one facet type
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Filtering is purely visual — it doesn't modify the facets, just makes it easier to find
        and select specific types in the list. The map canvas always shows all facets regardless
        of the filter.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- CLONING -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Cloning Facets
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Clone Facet</Bold> feature allows you to quickly create multiple facets with
        the same properties without repeatedly opening the Add Facets dialog. This dramatically
        speeds up building construction.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        How to Clone a Facet
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select a facet by clicking it on the map view or in the Facets list. The facet
                is highlighted and its properties are loaded.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click the <Bold>Clone Facet</Bold> button in the toolbar (looks like two overlapping
                squares). You immediately enter <Bold>draw mode</Bold> with a copy of the facet's
                properties loaded.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Draw the new facets on the map as normal. All properties (height, Y offset, style,
                flags) are inherited from the original facet.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Right-click</Bold> when finished drawing.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_clone_facet.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Clone Facet button in toolbar (overlapping squares icon) and facet selected on map ready to clone
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        When to Use Cloning
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Drawing multiple walls with the same height, style, and Y offset
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Adding a series of fences with consistent properties
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Creating repetitive structures (e.g., a row of identical building sections)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- TRANSFERRING -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Transferring Facets Between Buildings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        If you accidentally add a facet to the wrong building, you can <Bold>transfer</Bold>
        it to another building without deleting and recreating it. The facet's properties and
        position are preserved — only its parent building changes.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        How to Transfer a Facet
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                In the Facets list, <Bold>right-click</Bold> the facet you want to transfer.
                A context menu appears.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select <Bold>Transfer Facet...</Bold> from the menu. The <Bold>Transfer Facet</Bold>
                dialog appears.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Choose the <Bold>target building</Bold> from the dropdown list. This is the building
                the facet will be moved to.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click <Bold>Transfer</Bold>. The facet is moved to the new building and now appears
                in that building's Facets list.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_transfer_facet.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Transfer Facet dialog showing target building dropdown and Transfer button
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Transferring does not change the facet's position, height, texture, or any other property.
        It simply moves organizational ownership from one building container to another.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- MOVING BUILDINGS -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Moving Buildings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Move Building</Bold> feature allows you to relocate an entire building —
        including all facets, textures, walkables, roof tiles, and PAP flags — to a new location
        on the map. You can either <Bold>move</Bold> (preserving the building ID) or
        <Bold>copy</Bold> (creating a clone with a new ID).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        How to Move a Building
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select the building from the Buildings list.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click the <Bold>Move Building</Bold> button in the toolbar (blue-colored button).
                The building's footprint is captured and <Bold>cut from the map</Bold> (textures,
                walkables, and PAP flags are removed from the original location).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                A <Bold>blue ghost preview</Bold> of the building appears under your cursor,
                showing where it will be placed.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Move your cursor to the desired location and <Bold>click</Bold>. The
                <Bold>Place Building</Bold> dialog appears.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Choose an option:
            </Paragraph>
            <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
                <ListItem>
                    <Paragraph>
                        <Bold>Move</Bold> — Moves the building to the new location, preserving its
                        building ID and all references.
                    </Paragraph>
                </ListItem>
                <ListItem>
                    <Paragraph>
                        <Bold>Copy</Bold> — Creates a clone at the new location with a new building ID.
                        The original building remains in its original location.
                    </Paragraph>
                </ListItem>
            </List>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click <Bold>Place</Bold>. The building is placed at the new location.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_move.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Move Building in progress showing blue ghost preview of building under cursor, and Place Building dialog with Move/Copy options
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Move vs Copy:</Run>
                <LineBreak/>
                <LineBreak/>
                <Run>• Use</Run>
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Move</Run>
                <Run>when you want to relocate a building to a better position. The building ID stays the same, so any mission references remain valid.</Run>
                <LineBreak/>
                <LineBreak/>
                <Run>• Use</Run>
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Copy</Run>
                <Run>when you want to duplicate a building to create multiple identical structures. Each copy gets a new building ID and can be independently modified.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- DELETING -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Deleting Buildings and Facets
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        You can delete individual facets or entire buildings (including all their facets) using
        either the toolbar buttons or keyboard shortcuts.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Deleting a Facet
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To delete a single facet:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select the facet from the Facets list or click it directly on the map canvas.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Either:
            </Paragraph>
            <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
                <ListItem>
                    <Paragraph>
                        Click the <Bold>Delete Facet</Bold> button in the toolbar, or
                    </Paragraph>
                </ListItem>
                <ListItem>
                    <Paragraph>
                        Press the <Bold>Delete</Bold> key on your keyboard.
                    </Paragraph>
                </ListItem>
            </List>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph>
        The facet is immediately removed from the map and the Facets list. If the facet was part
        of a closed polygon, the polygon is now open and the Auto-Build system will no longer
        treat it as an enclosure.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Deleting a Building
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To delete an entire building (including all of its facets):
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select the building from the Buildings list.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Either:
            </Paragraph>
            <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
                <ListItem>
                    <Paragraph>
                        Click the <Bold>Delete Building</Bold> button in the toolbar, or
                    </Paragraph>
                </ListItem>
                <ListItem>
                    <Paragraph>
                        Press the <Bold>Delete</Bold> key on your keyboard.
                    </Paragraph>
                </ListItem>
            </List>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                A confirmation dialog appears (since deleting a building is a destructive action).
                Click <Bold>Yes</Bold> to confirm.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph>
        The building and all of its facets are permanently removed from the map. The building
        ID is freed and can be reused by a new building.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Warning:</Run>
                <Run>Deleting a building is irreversible (unless you immediately use Undo). If you accidentally delete a complex building, you will need to recreate it from scratch. Consider using the Move Building feature instead if you just want to relocate it.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Tips and Best Practices
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Use <Bold>bulk editing</Bold> (double-click polygon groups) when you need to
                change properties for an entire building layer. It's much faster than editing
                each facet individually.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Use <Bold>color pill filtering</Bold> when working on complex buildings with many
                facet types. For example, filter to show only doors when checking door placement,
                or only ladders when verifying climbing paths.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Use <Bold>Clone Facet</Bold> liberally. It's the fastest way to create multiple
                facets with the same properties without repeatedly opening dialogs.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                If you accidentally add a facet to the wrong building, use <Bold>Transfer Facet</Bold>
                rather than deleting and recreating it. Transferring preserves all properties and
                position.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Use <Bold>Move Building (Copy mode)</Bold> to quickly duplicate identical structures
                across your map. This is perfect for creating rows of houses, repeating fence
                sections, or standardized warehouse layouts.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                When deleting facets, if you make a mistake you can immediately press
                <Bold>Ctrl+Z</Bold> to undo (if undo is supported in the current version).
                Otherwise, be careful before deleting complex facets or buildings.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The Facets list displays <Bold>Y:</Bold> (Y offset) and <Bold>H:</Bold> (Height)
                for each facet, so you can quickly identify which layer a facet belongs to without
                selecting it.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

</FlowDocument>
